{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19174"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19174"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.59,0.14,0.05,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11908"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2419"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5431"},{"type":"tags","id":"9636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMultiple patients present to the emergency department with acute gastroenteritis symptoms over a 24-hour period. The symptoms include severe diarrhoea and vomiting. Several patients report eating at the same restaurant within the past 48 hours. Clinical staff suspect a potential outbreak situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial assessment reveals eight affected patients, with three requiring intravenous fluid replacement. The emergency department is concerned about their capacity to manage additional cases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in managing this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Collect specimens from affected patients","Establish a hospital response team","Begin contact tracing of cases","Implement visitor restrictions","Create a case definition"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate first step is \u003Cstrong\u003Eestablishing a hospital response team\u003C/strong\u003E. This multidisciplinary team coordinates the outbreak response and typically includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfection control practitioners\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmergency department representatives\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinical microbiologists\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHospital executives\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPublic health officials\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile other actions are important, they should follow team formation:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollecting specimens from affected patients\u003C/strong\u003E requires standardised protocols that should be established by the response team first. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeginning contact tracing of cases\u003C/strong\u003E cannot be effectively implemented without a clear case definition and systematic approach developed by the response team. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImplementing visitor restrictions\u003C/strong\u003E needs to be coordinated across departments with appropriate oversight from the response team. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreating a case definition\u003C/strong\u003E requires input from multiple stakeholders to ensure it captures all relevant cases while maintaining specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe response team provides leadership, coordinates communication between departments, allocates resources, and ensures a systematic approach to managing the outbreak. They can also liaise with external agencies such as public health departments and food safety authorities given the possible food-borne source.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Initial outbreak management in hospitals requires rapid notification of key stakeholders and formation of a response team","Hospital outbreak management teams should include infection control, clinical staff, laboratory and management representatives","Clear communication channels and defined roles are essential for effective hospital outbreak response","A systematic approach to outbreak investigation follows established steps in a logical sequence"],"references":["Surveillance and outbreak management of water-related infectious diseases associated with water-supply system. Copenhagen: WHO Regional Office for Europe; 2019. Licence: CC BY-NC-SA 3.0 IGO."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19174"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67839"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T20:30:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T09:33:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11908"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82703"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"